<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-090-002  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 090 002.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Reseller News  Nov 5 1990 n393 p48(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Translation: area of opportunity or closed door? (translatingsoftware for international markets)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Stal, Eric.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Many domestic software products marketed in other countries arefalling short of the full sales potential because many US vendorsare either unwilling or unable to offer foreign users a suitablytranslated package.andP;  Translation gives vendors and distributorswho understand the current issues both a challenge and anopportunity.andP;  US vendors are becoming more and more dependent oninternational trade, which accounts for an average of 41 percentof sales in firms with revenue over $50 million.andP;  US companiescould originally ship goods as is and have them sell reasonablywell.andP;  But the competition is becoming more demanding anddistributors are citing a demand not merely for translated goodsbut for well-translated goods.andP;  These translations should be donein the respective countries and facilitated by personnel livingand working in the specific areas and cultures.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Software PackagesMarketing StrategyInternational TradeForeign Languages.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>